name: Mike Lee
content:
Happy Military Spouse Appreciation Day!

We owe a great debt of gratitude to our military and their families who give so much to protect our nation. Among the many challenges that military families face, one of the greatest is that spouses working in fields requiring occupational licenses suffer huge setbacks to their careers. That is why I introduced the Military Spouse Licensing Relief Act.

This bill would simply ensure that when servicemembers are relocated on military orders, their spouses can receive reciprocity for professional licenses across state lines. If you, your spouse, a family member, or friend are experiencing the burden of new licensing requirements due to a military change of station order and would benefit from this change, I would be grateful to hear your story. Feel free to share your story to further raise attention, and use the hashtag #SupportMilitarySpouses.

To all military and their spouses, thank you for your service, hard work, and dedication.

LEE.SENATE.GOV
Sen. Lee Introduces Bipartisan Bill to Help Military Families

content:
Thank you to all the Vermonters I visited with this week in Addison and Rutland counties. name: Chris Van Hollen
content:
Over the last few days, I traveled to Sudan & the United Arab Emirates with U.S. Senator Chris Coons as part of an official trip to support the transition to democracy in Sudan, promote humanitarian relief to refugees of the conflict in Ethiopia, and meet with leadership in both countries on issues of mutual interest and concern.

We began our trip in the U.A.E., which will be the site of the Dubai World Expo. In a sign for a more hopeful world, they are hosting pavilions from friends and foes alike. While there, we visited our troops at Al Dhafra Air Base to thank them for their service. They not only play a vital security role in the region, but will be facilitating the safe withdrawal of U.S. forces from Afghanistan. Additionally, we met with U.A.E. leadership to exchange views and discuss our security partnership and ways to expand trade and investment. We also expressed mutual support for the Abraham Accords and the removal of U.A.E. forces from Yemen and noted the positive role they could play in resuming the JCPOA and reducing regional conflict.

Following our visit to the U.A.E., we traveled to Sudan. The U.S. has a key role to play in supporting Sudan‚Äôs journey from dictatorship toward democracy. The ousting of Dictator Omar Hassan Ahmad al-Bashir in the peaceful revolution about two years ago brings fresh hope, and the U.S. should be a full partner with the Sudanese people as they seek a better future. The new Prime Minister, Cabinet, and Sovereign Council are working diligently to move from authoritarian rule to rule of law and to separation of religion and state. It‚Äôs important that the Sudanese Armed Forces be placed under a single command and that they proceed as planned to full civilian control of the government.

Sudan is now home to over 3.6 million refugees and displaced people as a result of years of conflicts. Most recently, there has been an influx of over 60,000 refugees fleeing the conflict in Ethiopia. We visited the Um Rakuba refugee camp to listen to the plight of people fleeing the Tigray Region of Ethiopia. I‚Äôm grateful to USAID - US Agency for International Development, the World Food Programme, and the UNHCR, the UN Refugee Agency for their humanitarian efforts there. The Biden Administration is doing everything it can to end the fighting in Ethiopia and resolve regional disputes.

I want to thank all of the U.S. Embassy personnel in Sudan and the U.A.E. and other posts around the world for the work they do ‚Äì often at great personal risk and sacrifice ‚Äì to serve our country. I'm proud to be the Co-Chair of the Foreign Service Caucus. As President Biden has said, it is vital that we strengthen our relationships abroad and work to advance the rule of law, human rights and the peaceful resolution of conflicts in order to bolster our prosperity and security here at home.

name: Dan Sullivan
content:
Interior Secretary Deb Haaland callously chose to restrict millions of acres of federal land available to Alaska Native veterans selecting their congressionally-mandated land allotments that they missed due to their service during the Vietnam War. The opportunity came about as a result of my provision in the 2019 Dingell Act.

Gov. Mike Dunleavy and I penned an op-ed in the Juneau Empire outlining a new legislative effort to make state lands available to these Alaska Native veterans. Many veterans and their heirs would have the opportunity to select lands in their regions. I applaud the state for stepping in to help correct an injustice and honor the sacrifice of our veterans, even when the Biden administration refuses.

name: James M. Inhofe

Like our service members, military spouses bear a huge burden and sacrifice so much.

One way I‚Äôve tried to ease the burden for our military spouses, in the annual defense authorization bill. is by expanding opportunities for them to continue their careers as they navigate frequent moves associated with military service. content: I was excited to see the Alaska Drilling & Completions new, low footprint drilling rig, called the DeLorean Rig, which can be used for exploration and testing. This innovative design is installed entirely by helicopter and will not require ice roads for operations. The feet can sit directly on the tundra and will not transfer heat so no permafrost thaw problems to deal with. The rig is modified from a mining rig design but in the O&G industry, can be used to drill test and exploration wells up to 8000 feet. Operations will be able to expand year round, making summer exploration more viable and a smaller footprint means no gravel pads or ice roads.

WATCH: Students at Green Bank Elementary-Middle School had an out-of-this-world experience this week when they had the opportunity to make contact with Astronaut Mark Vande Hei on the International Space Station. The students asked excellent questions, and I couldn‚Äôt be more proud of them! Congratulations to GBEMS for their remarkable achievement of being chosen for the Amateur Radio on the International Space Station Program, where only a handful of schools across the world get selected for the opportunity to talk to astronauts in space. https://www.facebook.com/GreenBankObservatory/videos/1645570398968758

Green Bank Observatory was live.
May 7 at 8:00 AM ¬∑

How would you feel if you could talk to an astronaut, orbiting nearly 200-miles above you in space? Join us as students from Green Bank Elementary-Middle School (GBEMS) talk to an astronaut on the International Space Station LIVE!

This contact is made possible by Amateur Radio on the International Space Station (ARISS), an international program that inspires students around the world to pursue careers in science, technology, engineering and math.

Support was also given by the Snowshoe Foundation, The Durbin Lions Club, the Eight Rivers Amateur Radio Club, and several staff from the Green Bank Observatory. Special thanks to GBEMS Principal Julie Shiflet and Science Teacher Anne Smith.

name: John Boozman
content:
The Arkansas Democrat-Gazette / ArkansasOnline.com reports on the latest with I-57 and the briefing my office helped organize with ARDOT in Walnut Ridge this week to give a status update on the project.

I authored a provision in the transportation appropriations bill in 2016 to designate the Future I-57 route.

Business owners, civic leaders and travelers all understand the importance of connecting Northeast and Central Arkansas to this major interstate because it creates economic growth and development opportunities and allows for increased ease of movement. I am pleased to have been updated on the latest developments with the effort to plan and complete the construction of an interstate-quality highway and bring I-57 from the Missouri border all the way to North Little Rock. I look forward to further helping make this vision a reality.

name: Brian Schatz
content:
When we talk about the student loan debt crisis, we're not just talking about tuition. We're talking about the real costs to students and their families ‚Äî which includes books, room and board, transportation, and supplies. These expenses have forced 45 million Americans to take on debt to cover the full cost of their education. That's what makes the Debt-Free College Act unique: It goes beyond tuition to restore the path to affordable college.

I reintroduced this bill so we can bring states back to the table and leverage federal dollars to reinvest in public higher education.

name: Ken Calvert
content:
Today‚Äôs jobs report was a major disappointment. Economists expected gains of around 1 million jobs, but only 266,000 were added. As noted in this article, that‚Äôs ‚Äúthe biggest miss, relative to expectations, in decades.‚Äù So, what‚Äôs behind this weak economic recovery? The slow pace of reopening schools continues to keep many parents at home instead of the workplace and we continue to see net job losses for women throughout the economy. In some cases we have overcooked the amount of federal benefits and direct payments to workers to the point where they have a disincentive to rejoin the workforce. Many other workers and employers, especially in the travel and tourism industry, continue to be negatively impacted by restrictions on the operations of their business. The path to more jobs and economic growth is clear and doesn‚Äôt cost the government a dime ‚Äì reopen our schools and economy.

name: Dan Sullivan

Today, 97 years since the founding of the U.S. Foreign Service, we offer our sincere gratitude to the courageous, hard-working men and women of this crucial diplomatic corps. Our country relies on Foreign Service officers to engage with governments, businesses and individuals around the world, all with the aim of promoting America‚Äôs interests, strengthening our national security, and assisting U.S. citizens.

Two ways we can better support our Foreign Service officers is to prioritize their access to State Department opportunities at the conclusion of their service, and also expand private-sector employment opportunities for the family members of officers where they serve. I‚Äôve reintroduced legislation with my colleague, Senator Chris Van Hollen of Maryland, to accomplish these goals and support the important work of our Foreign Service officers.

Our public workforce is crucial to serving the American people‚Äîfrom fighting fires, to discovering cures to life threatening diseases, to protecting our national security, to caring for Veterans, to working on the front lines of this pandemic, to helping constituents in need, and so much more. During this Public Service Recognition Week, I want to express my gratitude for all they do for our country.

I am also thankful to those public servants in my office who work diligently to respond to constituent needs. Here, Austin, a member of our team, explains the constituent service work done by congressional offices as part of Public Service Recognition Week. Connecting folks in our state with the federal services they need and deserve is a key part of the work my team does, and the dedication of our staff is crucial to this effort.

name: Tom Cole
content:
Great news! The entry deadline for the 2021 Congressional Art Competition has been extended. If you are a high school artist from the Fourth District of Oklahoma and have not yet submitted your artwork, there is still time to do so. Submissions can now be dropped off at any of my three district offices (Norman, Lawton or Ada) or at the Ardmore Chamber of Commerce until 4 p.m. on May 28.

The top prize includes display of the winning artwork for one year in the Cannon tunnel leading to the United States Capitol like the artwork pictured here from the Fourth's District's 2020 winner.

More information, including submission release forms and contest rules, can be found on my website here: https://cole.house.gov/services/art-competition

For additional information or any last-minute questions, please call my Norman office at (405) 329-6500.
